from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Braham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Braham in Spofforth (Yorkshire) or Brantham in Suffolk (recorded as <i>Braham</i> in 1198). Braham in Yorkshire was probably named with the Old English personal name <i>Brahha</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. Brantham in Suffolk means ‘the steep homestead’, from Old English <i>brant</i> ‘steep’ + <i>hām</i>.","Irish and Scottish: shortened form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’. Compare   Brain  .","Jewish: shortened form of   Abraham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brain","meanings":["English: apparently a nickname from Middle English <i>brain</i> ‘brain, mind’, probably short for <i>brainwod</i> ‘mad in the mind, furious’. Compare   Brainard  .","Irish (Down) and Scottish: shortened Anglicized form of Irish <b>Mac an Bhreitheamhan</b>, Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bhreitheamhan</b> ‘son of the judge’, from <i>breitheamh</i> ‘judge’. Compare   Braham   2."]},{"name":"Bream","meanings":["English:","nickname for a fierce or energetic person, from Middle English <i>brem(e)</i>, <i>brim(me)</i> ‘fierce, vigorous’ (from Old English <i>brēme</i> ‘famous, noble’), or from a Middle English form of the Old English personal name <i>Brēme</i> with the same meaning.","variant of   Braham  ."]},{"name":"Brame","meanings":["English (Suffolk and Norfolk): variant of   Braham  .","German (also <b>Bräme</b>): variant of   Brahm   2. The surnames <i>Brame</i> and <i>Bräme</i> are very rare in Germany.","French: nickname from Old Occitan <i>brame</i> ‘cry, howl’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is 